ADG became the second most popular in Germany
Anti-immigrant “Alternative for Germany” breaks another record of popularity, and Angela Merkel ratings fall.
Apparently, the Germans began to get tired of Angela Merkel's immigration policy, which made the country a coveted target for millions of refugees from the Middle East.
Most clearly this is evidenced by recent polls, according to which the anti-immigrant party “Alternative for Germany” is becoming more popular, and the positions of the ruling bloc Merkel and Seehofer are weakening.
This week, the ADG broke another record, rising to the second place in the ranking of popular sympathy.
Right conservatives with 17 percent of popularity managed to bypass the Social Democrats, who have about 16 percent.
The gap of one percentage point can be written off for statistical error, but it is important to note the fact that the ADG of a small group of eurosceptic economists, created in 2013 managed to turn into a serious political force.
Leadership in the overall standings still continues to hold the ruling bloc of HSS/CDU, which has about 30 percent.
However, there is a tendency to lose points - back in April the support of Angela Merkel block was four percentage points higher.
The personal rating of the German Chancellor, who heads the German government for the fourth consecutive term, is also reduced.
Today in support of Angela Merkel speak 48 percent of Germans, which is 7 percent lower than last year.
We will add that after Social Democrats are “green” (15%), left (11%) and liberals (10%).
Evolution of “Alternatives”
The party “Alternative for Germany” was founded in September 2012 on the basis of the group “Alternative Choice 2013", which included people from the Christian Democratic Union.
The group initially opposed the government policy, but initially dealt with only economic issues, including the euro and EU interaction.
At the same time, the group opposed the “sponsorship” of Germany of the weak economies of the EU, did not exclude the possibility of returning to the German mark and the full withdrawal of the country from the European Union.
With the deepening immigration crisis, the political platform of the ADG has expanded.
In 2013, the group formed into a full-fledged party, which occupied a niche of Euroskeptics and began to harshly criticize the government for the failure of immigration policy.
In the last parliamentary elections in 2017, the ADG managed to break through to the Bundestag for the first time, gaining 94 seats (out of 709).
Two representatives of “Alternative for Germany” get seats in the European Parliament.
