To such conclusions experts came, observing with the help of the camera HSC (Hyper Suprime-Cam) of the Subaru telescope for about ten million galaxies.
Having traced the distribution of dark matter and dark energy, which account for more than 95 per cent of the energy mass of the observed world, scientists working under the standard cosmological model ΛCDM (Λ Cold Dark Matter), estimated the pace of expansion of the universe, which turned out to be slightly slower than previously thought.
Subaru observatory press release notes that the observations provided a detailed three-dimensional map of the distribution of matter in the universe, and the data of the European space telescope Planck $ clarified the restrictions imposed on the parameters of the ΛCDM.
