The main Macedonian oppositionist refused to vote in referendum
In Macedonia on Sunday, September 30, there is a referendum on the intergovernmental treaty with Greece on renaming the Republic of Macedonia.
Citizens are asked to answer one question: “Do you support EU and NATO membership by accepting the agreement between the Republic of Macedonia and the Hellenic Republic?”
Nevertheless, Christian Mickoski, leader of the leading opposition party, the Internal Macedonian Revolutionary Organization - Democratic Party for Macedonian National Unity (VMRO - DPMNE), stated that $ will not vote in a referendum.
As explained a press - the party secretary Naum Stoilkovsky, Mickosky decided to abstain from voting to express the disagreement with the contract which considers “harmful”.
According to a press - the secretary, the present referendum resolves an issue of renaming the country and nothing more, whereas the strategic goal of party - to achieve membership in NATO and EU.
A week ago, Macedonian President Gheorghe Ivanov refused to participate in the referendum on September 30.
He explained that the name for the country he chose 27 years ago in a referendum on independence. The Macedonian leader considers the renaming of the country a negative factor.
“A new semi-sovereign state with a new name is created”, - Ivanov noted.
The agreement on the new official name of the former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia - the Republic of Northern Macedonia - was signed by the Foreign Ministers of Macedonia and Greece on 17 June this year during a solemn ceremony of on the shores of Lake Prespa, which runs the border between the two countries. $
This treaty should resolve the long-term dispute over the name of the country, as well as Skopje way to NATO and the EU, reminds TASS.
