EU allocates €1.5 million to aid victims in Indonesia
The European Union (EU) has allocated €1.5 million to Indonesia to deal with the consequences of the earthquake and tsunami.
This was reported on September 30 by the press service of the European Commission.
In order to monitor the provision of aid, the European Commission sent its experts to the region.
As it is noted, means will go for disinfection, and also providing victims with products, water, temporary shelters and medicines.
The Commission also provided the Indonesian authorities with access to satellite maps of the European Emergency Service Copernicus (Copernicus) to assess the damage.
The United States also expressed its readiness to assist in eliminating the consequences of the disaster, the head of the press service of the US State Department Heather Nauert said in a statement.
It is also reported that the US diplomatic mission in Indonesia did not receive reports about the injured American citizens.
